boots <- replicate(1000, (sample(x = sfdata$TotalPay, size = 148654, replace = T)))
boots_mean <- apply(boots, 2, mean)
quantile(boots_mean, probs = c(.025, .975))
##     2.5%    97.5% 
## 74520.02 75010.00
#The 95% Confidence Interval for the average Total Pay of jobs in SF using the BootStrap 
#Procedure is $74,497.94 to $75,048.52. The BootStrap Confidence Interval is just slightly 
#wider than the 95% t-interval, if at all.
#6

midhinge <- function(data) {
  quantile1 = quantile(data)[2]
  quantile2 = quantile(data)[4]
  quan_avg = (quantile1 + quantile2)/2
  return(quan_avg)
}


trimmed_mean <- function(data, percent_to_trim) {
  cutoff = round(percent_to_trim*length(data))
  data = sort(data)
  first_index = 1 + cutoff
  last_index = length(data) - cutoff
  trimmed_data = data[first_index:last_index]
  return(mean(trimmed_data))
}

boots_mid_hinge <- data.frame(apply(boots_mid, 2, midhinge))

  ggtitle("Midhinge")

#The values of the Confidence Intervals of the midhinge, trims, and median are approximately $4000
#less than the values of the Confidence Interval for the mean from above. However, the width of the 
#intervals are nearly identical at $500, except for the midhinge confidence interval where the 
#width of the interval is closer to $1000. I would use the either the median confidence interval 
#or the 5% trimmed bootstrap mean because the Confidence Intervals appear to be most resistant
#to outliers and skewness.
